Southern California Deserts

The Southern California Deserts are a dry and arid expanse situated in the rain shadow of western mountain ranges, causing their dry landscapes. The Deserts are made up from the Mojave Desert and a part of the Sonoran Desert known as the Colorado Desert. They have similar geological features such as cliffs, peaks, canyons, dry washes, sand dunes, and large dry lake playas.

Both deserts have a hot-desert climate, meaning very little annual rainfall and scorching hot temperatures. The Sonoran experiences slightly hotter temperatures than the Mojave and has two rainy seasons: winter and late summer. The environment of the deserts has led to the evolution of unique species, like the Joshua tree, barred and prickly pear cactus, pinyon pine, California fan palm, Mojave ground squirrel, and Amargosa vole.

The climate of the region makes it unpopular for urban areas, however, few exist; most notably Palm Springs. Significant areas and landmarks of the Southern California Desert region include Death Valley, Coachella Valley, Kelso Dunes, and Joshua Tree Forest.
